Invocation

लक्षमीनारायणं नत्वा पूर्णबोधान्गुरुनपि ।
कुर्मः श्रीकृष्णगीतायाभाष्याद्युक्तार्थसंग्रहम् ॥

lakṣamīnārāyaṇaṃ natvā pūrṇabodhāngurunapi |
kurmaḥ śrīkṛṣṇagītāyābhāṣyādyuktārthasaṃgraham ||

Word-by-word: लक्षमीनारायणं नत्वा - Bowing to Laxmi Narayana; पूर्णबोधान् + गुरुन् + अपि - also to guru Madhwacharya (poorNa = full; bodha = knowledge); कुर्मः - we will do;  श्रीकृष्णगीताया - Shri Krishna's Gita; भाष्या + आदि + उक्त + अर्थ = speak the meaning given in the bhAshya (of Madhwacharya) and other; संग्रहम् - in brief.

Translation: Bowing down to Laxmi Narayana and also to guru Madhwacharya, we will give the meaning of Shri Krishna's Bhagavad Gita briefly as explained in the Bhaashya (of Madhwacharya) and others.




Introduction

"स्त्रीशूद्रब्रह्मबंधूनां त्रयी न श्रुतिगोचरा ।
कर्मश्रेयसि मूढानां श्रॆय ऎवं भवॆदिह ।
इति भारतमाख्यानं क्रपया मुनिना कृतम् ॥"
[भा. पु. १. ४. २५]

इति भागवतोक्तया, ‘ वेदार्थज्ञानानधिकारणां स्त्रीशूद्रादीनां धर्मज्ञानद्वारा मोक्षॊ भवेद् ’ इति भगवान्वेदव्यासः संभवसभाऽरण्यविराटॊद्यॊगभीष्म द्रोणकर्णशल्यगदासौषुप्तिकशांति अनुशासनिकाश्वमेधिकमौसलमहाप्रस्थानस्वर्गारोहणभविष्यत्पर्वभेदेनाष्टादशपर्वत्मकं भरतं तत्र भीष्मपर्वणि भारतपारिजतमधुभूतां सर्वभारतार्थसंग्रहभूतां श्रीकृष्णार्जुनसंवादरूपां भगवद्गीतां निबबन्ध । ‘ तत्र पूर्वषट्के ज्ञानॊपायॊक्तिः । द्वितीयष्ट्के साधनोक्तिः । तृतीयषट्के प्रागुक्तस्य प्रपञ्चनं क्रियत ’ इति विवेकः । तत्राद्याध्यायो द्वितीये कतिपयश्लोकाश्च कृष्णेनार्जुनबोधने प्रसक्तिसम्पादनाय प्रवृत्ताः । तत्रायमर्थः ।


"strīśūdrabrahmabaṃdhūnāṃ trayī na śrutigocarā |
karmaśreyasi mūḍhānāṃ śreya evaṃ bhavediha |
iti bhāratamākhyānaṃ krapayā muninā kṛtam ||"
[bhā. pu. 1. 4. 25]

iti bhāgavatoktayā, ‘ vedārthajñānānadhikāraṇāṃ strīśūdrādīnāṃ dharmajñānadvārā mokṣo bhaved ’ iti bhagavānvedavyāsaḥ saṃbhavasabhā:'raṇyavirāṭodyogabhīṣma droṇakarṇaśalyagadāsauṣuptikaśāṃti anuśāsanikāśvamedhikamausalamahāprasthānasvargārohaṇabhaviṣyatparvabhedenāṣṭādaśaparvatmakaṃ bharataṃ tatra bhīṣmaparvaṇi bhāratapārijatamadhubhūtāṃ sarvabhāratārthasaṃgrahabhūtāṃ śrīkṛṣṇārjunasaṃvādarūpāṃ bhagavadgītāṃ nibabandha | ‘ tatra pūrvaṣaṭke jñānopāyoktiḥ | dvitīyaṣṭke sādhanoktiḥ | tṛtīyaṣaṭke prāguktasya prapañcanaṃ kriyata ’ iti vivekaḥ | tatrādyādhyāyo dvitīye katipayaślokāśca kṛṣṇenārjunabodhane prasaktisampādanāya pravṛttāḥ | tatrāyamarthaḥ |

Word-by-word: स्त्री + शूद्र + ब्रह्मबंधूनां - women, shudras, men belonging to brahmaNa, kshatriya, vaishya classes without having undergone the proper samskArAs; त्रयी - these three; न - not; श्रुति - vedas; गोचरा - attainable; कर्मश्रेयसि - for excellence in their work; मूढानां - less intelligent people; श्रॆय - benefit; ऎवं - thus; भवॆत् - let it be; इह - this; इति - thus; भारतम् + आख्यानं - the Mahabharata was told; क्रपया - out of compassion; मुनिना - by sage (Vedavyasa); कृतम् - done.

इति भागवतोक्तया - the Bhagavata says this; वेदार्थ + ज्ञान - the meaning and special knowledge in the Vedas; अनधिकारणां - do not have the authority; स्त्री + शूद्र + आदीनां - women, shudras, and others; धर्म - dharma; ज्ञान - jnana;  द्वारा - through; मोक्षॊ - liberation; भवेद् - exists; इति - this; भगवान्वेदव्यासः - Lord Vedavyasa; संभव + सभा आरण्य + विराट + उद्यॊग + भीष्म द्रोण + कर्ण + शल्य + गदासौषुप्तिक + शांति अनुशासनिक + अश्वमेधिक + मौसल + महाप्रस्थान + स्वर्गारोहण + भविष्यत्पर्व + भेदेन + अष्टादश + पर्वत्मकं भरतं - adi, sabha, vana, viraata, udyoga, bheeshma, droNa, karNa, shalya, sauptika, stri, shaanti, anushasana, ashvamedhika, ashramavasika, mausala, mahaprasthanika - the eighteen parvas of the Mahabharata;  तत्र - there; भीष्मपर्वणि - in the Bheeshma parva; भारत + पारिजत + मधु + भूतां -   like the nectar of the paarijata flower; सर्व + भारत + अर्थ + संग्रह + भूतां - is the essence of the entire Mahabharatha; श्रीकृष्ण + अर्जुन + संवाद + रूपां - in the form of a dialogue between Shri Krishna and Arjuna; भगवद्गीतां निबबन्ध - he put forward the Gita; तत्र पूर्वषट्के - there in the first six chapters; ज्ञान + उपाय + उक्ति: - method to gain knowledge is explained; द्वितीयष्ट्के साधनोक्तिः - in the second six chapters, the method for practising (sadhana); तृतीयषट्के - in the third set of six chapters;  प्रागुक्तस्य - of the previous utterance; प्रपञ्चनं - explanation; क्रियत - is done; इति + विवेकः - this is the distinction; तत्र + आद्य + द्वितीये + अध्यायो - there, in the first and second chapters; कतिपय - few; श्लोकाश्च - shlokas and; कृष्णेन - by Krishna; अर्जुन -  Arjuna; बोधने - instruction; प्रसक्ति + सम्पादनाय प्रवृत्ताः - exist to establish the topic of conversation; तत्र + अयम् + अर्थः - this is the meaning.


Translation: Women, shudras, and men belonging to the brahmaNa, kshatriya, vaishya classes who have not undergone the proper samskArAs - these three classes are not eligible for studying the Vedas. Out of compassion, sage Vedavyasa composed the Mahabharata, by which the unintelligent people can attain excellence in their work. [Bhagavata Purana 1.4.25].

This is said in the Bhagavata PuraNa. The path to liberation (mokSha) for women, shudras, and others (brahma bandhus) who do not have the authority to study the Vedas is through the knowledge of dharma. In the eighteen parvAs of the Mahabharata, the Bhagavad Gita is in the Bheeshma parva in the form of a dialogue between Shri Krishna and Arjuna and is like the nectar of the pArijata flower (a celestial flower). There, in the first six chapters, the method of gaining knowledge (jnana) is explained. In the second set of six chapters, the method of diligent practice (sAdhana) is explained. And, in the third set of six chapters, all that was previously explained is further elaborated. This is the distinction. And, there, a few shlokas of the first and second chapters establish the topic of conversation i.e., the instructions given by Krishna to Arjuna. This is the meaning. 




धृतराष्ट्र उवाच -
धर्मक्षेत्रे कुरुक्षेत्रे समवेता युयुत्सवः ॥
ममकाः पाण्डवाश्चैव किमकुरुवत सञ्जय ॥ १.१ ॥

[रा.वि] किम् इत्याह । धर्म इति धर्मसाधनभूमौ कुरुक्षेत्रे युयुत्सवः युद्दमिच्छन्त एव समवेता मिळिताः सन्तो मामका मदीयाः दुर्योधनादयः पाण्डवाश्च हे सञ्जय किमकुरुवत इति शब्दो योज्यः । पाण्डवानां भगवत्प्रियत्वं सर्वसाक्षिकमप्यजानन्धृतराष्ट्रः स्वपुत्राणां विजयविविदिषया सञ्जयं पपृच्छ इत्यर्थः ।


dhṛtarāṣṭra uvāca -
dharmakṣetre kurukṣetre samavetā yuyutsavaḥ ||
mamakāḥ pāṇḍavāścaiva kimakuruvata sañjaya || 1.1 ||

[rā.vi] kim ityāha. dharma iti dharmasādhanabhūmau kurukṣetre yuyutsavaḥ yuddamicchanta eva samavetā miḷitāḥ santo māmakā madīyāḥ duryodhanādayaḥ pāṇḍavāśca he sañjaya kimakuruvata iti śabdo yojyaḥ | pāṇḍavānāṃ bhagavatpriyatvaṃ sarvasākṣikamapyajānandhṛtarāṣṭraḥ svaputrāṇāṃ vijayavividiṣayā sañjayaṃ papṛccha ityarthaḥ |


Word-by-word: धृतराष्ट्र उवाच  - DhritarashTra says; किम् इत्याह - what? It is said here; धर्मक्षेत्रे - in the land of dharma; कुरुक्षेत्रे - in kurukshetra; समवेता - gathered together; युयुत्सवः - ready to fight; ममकाः - my sons; पाण्डवाः + च + एव - and the sons of Pandu; किम कुरुवत सञ्जय - what did they do Sanjaya.

धर्म इति धर्म साधन भूमौ कुरुक्षेत्रे - in Kurukshetra which is a place for performing one's dharma; युयुत्सवः - युद्दमिच्छन्त एव - yuyutsavaḥ  means desiring to fight; समवेता मिळिताः - samavetā means came together at that place; सन्तो मामका मदीयाः - mamakāḥ means my people; दुर्योधनादयः - duryodhana and others; पाण्डवाश्च - and sons of Pandu; हे सञ्जय - oh Sanjaya; किम कुरुवत - what did they do; इति शब्दो योज्यः - this is how the words are applied.  पाण्डवानां - of the Pandavas; भगवत +प्रियत्वं - the closeness to the Lord; सर्व + साक्षिकम् + अपि - also known to everyone; अजानन् + धृतराष्ट्रः - not known to DhritarashTra; स्वपुत्राणां - his own sons; विजय - victory; विविदिषया - wanting to know; सञ्जयं पपृच्छ - asked Sanjaya; इत्यर्थः - this is the meaning.

Shloka translation: "Oh Sanjaya - gathered together in Kurukshetra ready to fight, what did my sons and the Pandavas do?", said Dhritarashtra. 

Ra. Vi.: In Kurukshetre, the place favorable for performing one's dharma; yuyutsava means desirous to fight; samaveta means they came together at a place; mamakAh means my people; Duryodhana, sons of Pandu, and others what did they do Oh Sanjaya -- this is how the words are to be applied. The closeness of the Pandavas to Lord Krishna was known to everyone, but not known to Dhritarashtra. He asked Sanjaya this wanting to know about the victory of his sons. This is the meaning. 
	

सञ्जय उवाच -
दृष्ट्वा तु पाण्डवानीकं व्यूढं दुर्योधनस्तदा ।
आचार्यमुपसङ्गम्य राजा वचनमब्रवीत् ॥ १.२ ॥

धृतराष्ट्रप्रश्नस्य सञ्जय उत्तरमुक्तवान् इत्याह वैशंपायनो जनमेजयं प्रति । सञ्जय उवाच इत्यादि नवभि: श्लोकैः दुर्योधनकृतव्यापारमाह । दृष्ट्वा इत्यादिना राजा दुर्योधनः तु तदा युद्धार्थम मिलितसमये व्यूढम व्यूहात्मना रचितम पाण्डव-सैन्यम दृष्ट्वा तु दृष्ट्वा एव इति वा अतः अन्वयः । द्रोणाचार्य-समीपम् आगत्य वचनम् उवाच । 

sañjaya uvāca -
dṛṣṭvā tu pāṇḍavānīkaṃ vyūḍhaṃ duryodhanastadā |
ācāryamupasaṅgamya rājā vacanamabravīt || 1.2 ||

dhṛtarāṣṭrapraśnasya sañjaya uttaramuktavān ityāha vaiśaṃpāyano janamejayaṃ prati | sañjaya uvāca ityādi navabhi: ślokaiḥ duryodhanakṛtavyāpāramāha | dṛṣṭvā ityādinā rājā duryodhanaḥ tu tadā yuddhārthama militasamaye vyūḍhama vyūhātmanā racitama pāṇḍava-sainyama dṛṣṭvā tu dṛṣṭvā eva iti vā ataḥ anvayaḥ | droṇācārya-samīpam āgatya vacanam uvāca | 


Word-by-word: धृतराष्ट्र + प्रश्नस्य + सञ्जय + उत्तरम + उक्तवान् - Sanjaya replied to Dhritarashtra's question;  वैशंपायनो जनमेजयं प्रति - Vaishampaayana told Janamejaya; सञ्जय उवाच इत्यादि नवभि: श्लोकैः - starting with "Sanjaya told", the next nine shlokas; दुर्योधन + कृत + व्यापारम् आह - talks about what Duryodhana did; दृष्ट्वा इत्यादिना राजा - "dṛṣṭvā" till ;  दुर्योधनः तु - King Duryodhana; तदा युद्धार्थम मिलितसमये - then - implying the time when the armies were assembled seeking to fight; व्यूढम - व्यूहात्मना रचितम - in battle formation; पाण्डवसैन्यम - the pAnDava army; दृष्ट्वा तु दृष्ट्वैव - just by looking at; इति वा अतः अन्वयः - thus, in this way you can arrange the words; द्रोणाचार्य-समीपम् आगत्य  - came close to droNachArya; वचनम् उवाच - spoke the words. 

Shloka translation: Sanjaya replied - "By just observing the Pandava army in battle formation, King Duryodhana approached DroNacharya and spoke."

Ra. Vi.: Vaishampayana told Janamejaya that Sanjaya replied to Dhritarashtra's question. Starting from "sañjaya uvāca", the next nine shlokas talk about what Duryodhana did. Starting from "dṛṣṭvā" till "rājā", the words can be arranged thus - "Raja Duryodhana, by just looking at the Pandava army at that time (=ready to fight and arranged in battle formation) ".  He (=Duryodhana) came close to Dronacharya and spoke the following words.

Comment: Raghavendra Swamy brings out the fear in Duryodhana by stressing on the word "tu". By just looking at the Pandava army, Duryodhana approaches his teacher Dronacharya. 


पश्यैतां पाण्डुपुत्राणामाचार्य महतीं चमूम ।
व्यूढां द्रुपदपुत्रेण तव शिष्येण धीमता ॥ १.३ ॥

[रा. वि.] तद वचनम एव अनुवदति सञ्जय । पश्यैतां इत्यादिना हे आचार्य तव शिष्येण धीमता धृष्टद्युम्नेन व्यूढाम पाण्डुपुत्राणाम महतीम चमूम एताम सेनाम पश्य ।

paśyaitāṃ pāṇḍuputrāṇāmācārya mahatīṃ camūma |
vyūḍhāṃ drupadaputreṇa tava śiṣyeṇa dhīmatā || 1.3 ||

[rā. vi.] tada vacanama eva anuvadati sañjaya | paśyaitāṃ ityādinā he ācārya tava śiṣyeṇa dhīmatā dhṛṣṭadyumnena vyūḍhāma pāṇḍuputrāṇāma mahatīma camūma etāma senāma paśya |

Word-by-word: [रा. वि.] तद वचनम एव - these words; अनुवदति सञ्जय - Sanjaya repeated; पश्यैतां इत्यादिना "paśyaitāṃ" onwards;  हे आचार्य - oh teacher; तव शिष्येण - your student's; धीमता - intelligence; धृष्टद्युम्नेन - dhristadyumna's (son of Drupadal, hence he is referred to as drupadaputra); व्यूढाम - arrangement; पाण्डुपुत्राणाम - of the sons of Pandu; महतीम- great; चमूम - mighty; एताम सेनाम - this army; पश्य - see.

Ra. Vi.: From "paśyaitāṃ" onwards, Sanjaya repeated the following words. "Oh Teacher! Look at your intelligent student Dhristadyumna's arrangement of this great and mighty army of the sons of pAnDu."



अत्र शूरा महेष्वासा भीमार्जुनसमा युधि ।
युयुधानो विराटश्च द्रुपदश्च महारथः ॥ १.४ ॥

[रा. वि.] अत्र सेनायाम महेष्वासाः महाधानुष्काः युधि भीम-अर्जुन-समाः शूराः सन्ति । ते कः इत्यत आह । युयुधान इत्यादिना । महारथः इति प्रत्येकम अन्वेति ।


atra śūrā maheṣvāsā bhīmārjunasamā yudhi |
yuyudhāno virāṭaśca drupadaśca mahārathaḥ || 1.4 ||

[rā. vi.] atra senāyāma maheṣvāsāḥ mahādhānuṣkāḥ yudhi bhīma-arjuna-samāḥ śūrāḥ santi | te kaḥ ityata āha | yuyudhāna ityādinā | mahārathaḥ iti pratyekama anveti |

Word-by-word: अत्र सेनायाम - in this army; महेष्वासाः महाधानुष्काः - maheṣvāsāḥ means great archers; युधि - in battle; भीम-अर्जुन-समाः - similar to Bheema and Arjuna; शूराः सन्ति - there are brave warriors; ते कः - who are they?; इत्यत आह - it is mentioned here; युयुधान इत्यादिना Yuyudhana and others (Viraata, Drupada);  महारथः इति प्रत्येकम अन्वेति - the adjective mahārathaḥ is applied to each of them. 

Ra. Vi.: In this army, there are great archers comparable to Bheema and Arjuna in battle. Who are they? Yuyuddhana, Virata and Drupada. The adjective mahārathaḥ is applicable to each of them. 




धृष्टकेतुश्चेकितानः काशिराजश्च वीर्यवान ।
पुरुजित्कुन्तिभोजश्च शैब्यश्च नरपुंगवः ॥ १.५ ॥

[रा. वि.] वीर्यवान इति विशेषणं नरपुङ्गवो नरश्रेष्ठ इत्यापि त्रयणाम् ।


dhṛṣṭaketuścekitānaḥ kāśirājaśca vīryavāna |
purujitkuntibhojaśca śaibyaśca narapuṃgavaḥ || 1.5 ||

[rā. vi.] vīryavāna iti viśeṣaṇaṃ narapuṅgavo naraśreṣṭha ityāpi trayaṇām |

Word-by-word: वीर्यवान इति विशेषणं - the adjective vīryavāna; नरपुङ्गवो - bull among men; नरश्रेष्ठ - best among men; इत्यापि त्रयणाम् - also applicable to all three.

[rā. vi.] The adjective vīryavāna (=brave) is applicable to DhrisTiketu, Chekitana, Kaashiraja. narapuṅgava is also applicable to Purujita, Kuntibhoja, and Shaibya.


